  "local_port": 48046,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I restore misc files from phone?",
  "response": "Restoring miscellaneous files from your phone can be done in several ways depending on where the files were originally stored (internal storage, SD card, or cloud storage) and whether you have a backup. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you restore your files:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Restore from a Backup**\nIf you have a backup of your files, you can restore them easily.\n\n#### **Google Drive Backup (Android)**  \n- Go to **Settings** > **Google** > **Backup**.  \n- Check if your files were backed up to Google Drive.  \n- To restore, log in to the same Google account on your phone and follow the on-screen prompts to restore your backup.  \n\n#### **iCloud Backup (iPhone)**  \n- Go to **Settings** > **[Your Name]** > **iCloud** > **iCloud Backup**.  \n- If a backup exists, reset your phone and choose **Restore from iCloud Backup** during the setup process.  \n\n#### **Third-Party Backup Apps**  \nIf you used apps like Samsung Smart Switch, Dropbox, or OneDrive, open the app and restore the files from there.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Check the Recycle Bin or Trash**\nSome cloud storage services and file manager apps have a trash or recycle bin where deleted files are temporarily stored.\n\n- **Google Photos/Drive**: Open the app, go to the **Trash** section, and restore the files.  \n- **File Manager Apps**: Check the **Recycle Bin** or **Trash** folder in your file manager app (e.g., Files by Google, ES File Explorer).  \n\n---\n\n### **3. Use File Recovery Software**\nIf you didn\u2019t back up your files and they were accidentally deleted, you can try using file recovery software. This works best for files stored on internal storage or an SD card.\n\n#### **For Android**:  \n- Download a reputable file recovery app like **DiskDigger**, **EaseUS MobiSaver**, or **Dr.Fone**.  \n- Follow the app\u2019s instructions to scan and recover your files.  \n- Note: Rooting your phone may improve recovery chances, but it\u2019s risky.  \n\n#### **For iPhone**:  \n- Use apps like **Dr.Fone** or **iMobie PhoneRescue** to recover deleted files.  \n- Alternatively, connect your iPhone to a computer and use software like **iTunes** or **Finder** to restore from a backup.  \n\n---\n\n### **4. Check External Storage**\nIf your files were stored on an SD card or external storage, remove the card and connect it to a computer using a card reader. You can scan the card using file recovery software like **Recuva** or **PhotoRec**.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Cloud Sync Services**\nIf your files were synced to a cloud service like Google Drive, Dropbox, or OneDrive, log in to the service on your phone or computer and download the files.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Contact Customer Support**\nIf the files are critical and you can\u2019t recover them yourself, consider contacting your phone\u2019s manufacturer or a professional data recovery service.\n\n---\n\n### **Prevention Tips**  \nTo avoid losing files in the future:  \n- Regularly back up your phone to a cloud service or computer.  \n- Use an SD card for important files.  \n- Enable auto-sync for cloud storage apps.  \n\nLet me know if you need more help!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
